        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "Add Baileys WebSocket WhatsApp fake server",
        "body": "## What Problem This Solves\n\nWhatsApp fake-provider support depended on a Crabline-specific in-process socket factory. That made OpenClaw carry adapter glue instead of letting Baileys connect to a server-shaped mock.\n\n## Why This Change Was Made\n\nThis adds a Baileys-compatible WebSocket endpoint to the Crabline WhatsApp fake provider. The server handles the Baileys Noise handshake, responds to bootstrap/device/prekey queries, records encrypted outbound WebSocket stanzas, and exposes the URL in the fake-provider manifest as `endpoints.baileysWebSocketUrl`.\n\nThis also removes the older `@openclaw/crabline/whatsapp-socket-factory` export so callers use the server URL path instead of importing a local mock socket.\n\nRelated OpenClaw PR: https://github.com/openclaw/openclaw/pull/97697\n\n## User Impact\n\nConsumers can point Baileys at Crabline with `waWebSocketUrl` and keep WhatsApp channel code on the normal Baileys path. The existing Graph-style fake WhatsApp HTTP endpoints remain available for admin/webhook-style fixture traffic.\n\n## Evidence\n\n- `pnpm lint`\n- `pnpm test`\n- `pnpm test test/whatsapp-fake-server.test.ts`\n- `pnpm test test/openclaw.test.ts`\n- `pnpm test test/cli.test.ts`\n",
        "branch": "codex/whatsapp-baileys-websocket-server",
